questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production memory leak where the JVM eventually crashes with an `OutOfMemoryError` (OOM). The system uses a custom metadata cache to associate network connections with their raw configurations using the following implementation:

java
public class CustomMetadataCache {
    private final Map<ConnectionKey, Metadata> cache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public void cacheMetadata(ConnectionKey key, String rawData) {
        Metadata metadata = new Metadata(key, rawData);
        cache.put(key, metadata);
    }
}


Here, `ConnectionKey` represents a unique connection wrapper, and `Metadata` retains a reference to its corresponding `ConnectionKey` for logging purposes. Under profiling, you notice that garbage collection is unable to reclaim any of the discarded `ConnectionKey` objects.

You are debugging a production issue where updates made to elements inside a Hibernate-managed custom persistent collection (`PersistentBag`) fail to persist to the database. The modifications are executed as follows within a Spring-managed service:

java
@Service
public class InventoryService {
    @Autowired
    private WarehouseRepository warehouseRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void markItemsAsProcessed(Long warehouseId) {
        Warehouse warehouse = warehouseRepository.findById(warehouseId).orElseThrow();
        Collection<Item> items = warehouse.getItems(); // Custom PersistentBag

        CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            items.forEach(item -> item.setStatus("PROCESSED"));
        }).join();
    }
}


No errors are thrown, but the database updates are completely ignored upon transaction completion.
